{"title_page": "Bryce Hall", "text_new": "{{short description|American football cornerback}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n| name            = Bryce Hall\n| image           = \n| image_size      =\n| alt             =\n| caption         = \n| highschool      = [[Bishop McDevitt High School (Harrisburg, Pennsylvania)|Bishop McDevitt]] <br>(Harrisburg, PA)\n| school          = Virginia Cavaliers\n| currentnumber   = 34\n| currentposition = [[Cornerback]]\n| class           = [[Senior (education)|Senior]]\n| major           =\n| birth_date      =\n| birth_place     = \n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 1\n| weight_lb       = 200\n| bowlgames       = \n*[[2018 Belk Bowl]]\n*[[2017 Military Bowl]]\n| highlights      = *First-team All-ACC ([[2018 Atlantic Coast Conference football season|2018]])\n*Second-team [[All-American]] ([[2018 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2018]])\n*[[Athlon Sports]] first-team freshman All-ACC ([[2016 Atlantic Coast Conference football season|2016]])\n| pastschools     =\n* [[Virginia Cavaliers football|Virginia]] (2016\u20132019)\n|espn=4037584\n}}\n\n'''Bryce Hall''' is an American football [[cornerback]] who plays for the [[Virginia Cavaliers football|Virginia Cavaliers]]. He played high school football at [[Bishop McDevitt High School (Harrisburg, Pennsylvania)|Bishop McDevitt High School]] in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]].\nGirlfriend: Emily Rose Potts.\n\n==High school career==\nPlaying at [[Bishop McDevitt High School (Harrisburg, Pennsylvania)|Bishop McDevitt High School]] in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]], Hall excelled at both wide receiver and defensive back. He was rated as a two-star prospect, and chose [[Virginia Cavaliers footbal|Virginia]] over only one other FBS scholarship offer, [[Coastal Carolina Chanticleers football|Coastal Carolina]].<ref name=\"RTD\">{{cite web |last1=Barber |first1=Mike |title=UVA star cornerback Bryce Hall will return for senior season |url=https://www.richmond.com/sports/college/schools/university-virginia/uva-star-cornerback-bryce-hall-will-return-for-senior-season/article_4e0669e4-0bb7-11e9-9d4f-0fda3f9e858d.html |website=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]] |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref> He originally committed to UVA as an athlete, with more accolades on the offensive side of the ball.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ramspacher |first1=Andrew |title=Freshman Hall a big hit in Virginia's secondary |url=https://www.dailyprogress.com/cavalierinsider/freshman-hall-a-big-hit-in-virginia-s-secondary/article_0b6fa5cc-90bd-11e6-b766-4ff111b6d602.html |website=[[The Daily Progress]] |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Collegiate career==\nReceiving playing time as a true freshman in 2016, Hall became a starter in the defensive lineup after switching from wide receiver to cornerback. He continued to build during his sophomore season, starting every game.<ref name=\"RTD\" />\n\nHall led all collegiate players in pass breakups his junior year, and he explored the possibility of entering the [[2019 NFL Draft]], even getting a grade from the NFL's Draft Advisory Board. After Virginia beat South Carolina in the [[2018 Belk Bowl]], Hall announced that he would return to UVA for his senior year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Counts |first1=Ron |title=Bryce Hall returning to Virginia for his senior season |url=https://www.dailyprogress.com/sports/cavalierinsider/bryce-hall-returning-to-virginia-for-his-senior-season/article_c09b8d6e-97ee-5591-8f05-b53b6a20d475.html |website=[[The Daily Progress]] |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref> Mock drafts for 2019 had Hall going as high as the first round.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shiers |first1=Mike |title=Virginia CB Bryce Hall Focused on Bowl Game, Not Accolades |url=https://www.nbc29.com/story/39645585/virginia-cb-bryce-hall-focused-on-bowl-game-not-accolades |website=[[WVIR]] |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref> Despite earning first team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] and second team All-American honors after his junior year, Hall cited a desire to improve himself and the Cavalier program as a main reason to stay for his senior season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Teel |first1=David |title=Bryce Hall's return reflects U.Va.'s upward trajectory |url=https://www.dailypress.com/sports/dp-spt-bryce-hall-returning-uva-1231-story.html |website=[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]] |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nPreliminary mock drafts before the 2019 season have projected Hall as a first-round prospect in the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trapasso |first1=Chris |title=2020 NFL Mock Draft: bengals take Justin Herbert, three WRs land in top 10 |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/news/2020-nfl-mock-draft-bengals-take-justin-herbert-three-wrs-land-in-top-10/ |website=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 12, 2019, in Virginia's sixth game of the season, Hall suffered an ankle injury in the second quarter against [[2019 Miami Hurricanes football team|Miami]] which required surgery, effectively ending his senior season and collegiate career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/team/_/id/258/virginia-cavaliers|title=Virginia cornerback Bryce Hall has ankle surgery, out for season|author=ESPN News Services|date=2019-10-13|website=[[ESPN.com]]|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://virginiasports.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=6513 Virginia Cavaliers biography]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Bryce}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Virginia Cavaliers football players]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football cornerback}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n| name            = Bryce Hall\n| image           = \n| image_size      =\n| alt             =\n| caption         = \n| highschool      = [[Bis